ZE=1>)<BR></FONT><A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fblacktower89939publicforum.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=36.topic><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Reply</FONT></A><BR><img src=http://www.cgocable.net/~focus23/bt/profiles/tesh1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">How The Tracking Skill Works (and it does)</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Ok, recently I was mentioning in guild spam that tracking worked and that rangers were completely out of their gourde when they complained over and over that tracking does work.  Immediately I got two responses from rangers in the guild who don't believe me.  So, I've decided to explain here how tracking works so that everybody can see it.  I want to get this out once and for all so that everybody can stop complaining about this skill.  It's NOT broken, it works perfectly well and here's how it works.<br>
<br>
HOW TRACKING WORKS (by Teshia Raye of Black Tower)<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Picture yourself as a level one ranger with a small invisible bubble around you that nobody can see.  It's a perfectly round bubble.  That's your range within which you can track objects.  So let's say you hit Track and you get five MOBs pops up, two bats, a mangy rat, a player, and an NPC.  Imagine also that you're grouped with the player on your list.  So here's how tracking works....<br>
<br>
The players you are grouped with always appear at the top of the list.  This is given precedence above everything else.  If you have five MOBs (in our example) and a whole mess of space underneath, it means that those five mobs/pcs/npcs are within the invisible tracking bubble.  If a MOB moves outside that bubble and you hit Track again, you'll get an updated list of 4 mobs/pcs/npcs with that MOB now gone.<br>
<br>
As new mobs/pcs/npcs enter that bubble, they are recorded in the order they entered the area.  The time they entered that bubble is remembered and this affects the way you see your list the next time you hit Track.  Let's use the same example from above but now it's twenty seconds later and three new MOBs have entered the tracking bubble since you last hit Track (this also assumes that nothing that was in the bubble has left the bubble within those twenty seconds).  First, a_skeleton04, then a_skeleton02, and finally, a_skeleton10.  The tracking window is now going to look like this:<br>
<br>
Finuala &lt;-- The PC you're grouped with<br>
a skeleton &lt;-- This is skeleton10 (the most recent)<br>
a skeleton &lt;-- This is skeleton02 (the second most recent)<br>
a skeleton &lt;-- This is skeleton04 (the third most recent)<br>
a bat<br>
Holly Windstalker &lt;-- The NPC<br>
a mangy rat<br>
a bat<br>
(followed by empty space below)<br>
<br>
Then, another mangy rat enters the bubble and one of the bats leaves the bubble:<br>
<br>
Finuala<br>
a mangy rat<br>
a skeleton<br>
a skeleton<br>
a skeleton<br>
Holly Windstalker<br>
a mangy rat<br>
a bat<br>
(followed by empty space below)<br>
<br>
Let's say a rare mob/npc suddenly pops within that bubble and it summons a pet soon after:<br>
<br>
Finuala<br>
Pyzjin Pet<br>
Pyzjin<br>
a mangy rat<br>
a skeleton<br>
a skeleton<br>
a skeleton<br>
Holly Windstalker<br>
a mangy rat<br>
a bat<br>
(followed by empty space below)<br>
<br>
This is great.  Now anything rares that pop within that bubble can instantly be found.  The down side is that if your bubble isn't big enough, you'll miss the pop of the MOB.  Now, that doesn't mean you won't see it.  If you run around the zone hitting Track over and over, you'll be sending new stuff through the bubble so quickly that eventually you might find the MOB.  The tracking bubble can be enlarged though.  Every time you improve your tracking skill, the bubble gets a little bit bigger.  A druid tracking bubble is fairly small, much like a low level ranger's tracking bubble.  This has it's advantages and disadvantages.  On the plus side, the lists remain small and if you see a MOB on your list, it's probably close by and easy to find.  On the down side, you'll miss a lot of potential items outside of that bubble and you'll get misreadings on where your party members are.<br>
<br>
What's that you say? That's a bug? No, it's no bug my friends.  Party members appear at the top of a list REGARDLESS of whether they're inside your tracking bubble or not.  In one sense, this is somewhat dangerous as it leads you to believe you can track them, which you may not always be able to do.  If they're inside the bubble, you'll be able to track them just fine.  If they're outside the bubble, you'll often get strange directions to those mobs, often the opposite direction of where they really are.  What's the point of that you ask? Well think about how tracking works in the real world.  If somebody is down the road from you and you're a tracker, you might be able to pick them up, but if they're too far, you could get led all over the place in the wrong directions.  So then the big question is, how do you know if they're inside your tracking bubble or not? You don't, and this is perhaps the flaw in Tracking as a skill.  It leads you to believe party members are always nearby and trackable, which they often are not.<br>
<br>
Now let's get back to the bubble.  A low level ranger tracking bubble and a high level druid bubble are somewhat the same.  A high level ranger tracking bubble is significantly larger.  So large in fact that a level 50+ ranger who is experienced at tracking (say a skill level of 190) could probably see anything that spawns in Dagnor's Cauldron if they stood right in the middle of the zone.  This is great stuff because basically, all they have to do is sit in the zone, keep hitting track and watch the list scroll downwards as new mobs popping in the zone appear near the top of the list and the old mobs roll off the bottom of the list.  They pretty much just have to wait until they see Bilge's name spawn at the top of the list and they're off and running after him.<br>
<br>
There are some down sides to this scrolling process as well.  It means that when tracking is as good as high level ranger tracking is, the list moves so fast with things popping in the zone, that a mob stays on a tracking list for all of a minute before it scrolls off the bottom.  Let's use an example from Sol B with a rare spawn.  Say everybody's doing Kobolds and nobody's doing bats and bugs, which is where the Guano Harvester, a rare mob, spawns.  It spawns and appears on top of your tracking list, but you never hit Track so you don't know it's up.  Minutes and minutes go by.  In that time, let's say 20-30 kobolds were killed off and new ones spawned in their place.  This means they've scrolled the Guano Harvester down the list, possibly right off the bottom of it.  Therefore, if you don't keep hitting tracking, you might scroll something valuable off the bottom, never to be tracked again unless it repops.  This again is another problem with the tracking window.  It needs a scroll bar.  My guess it, they KNOW it needs a scroll bar, they just don't want to be bothered implementing it or it's too much information to record so they feel it'll slow things down.<br>
<br>
Enter a busy zone sometime and hit Track.  You'll notice that as things get killed off, they start randomly dissapearing off the list, leaving holes.  This means the list isn't dynamically updated, so you have to keep hitting Track.  On the good side though, you don't have to cancel out of the tracking window to re-track.  If you have it set up as a hotkey (let's say it's F2 as an example), you can repeatedly hit F2 over and over again while viewing the tracking window and you'll see it appear to dynamically update, even though it's not doing that.  You'll still have to wait for the recovery delay, but it works.<br>
<br>
So yes, tracking could be better, and yes, it has it's up sides and down sides, but hey, nothing is perfect.<br>
<br>
But it's not broken.  That much I promise you.</font><P><OBJECT classid="clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000"
